snippet: An investigation into the death of an Estonian explosive ordnance disposal technician found that he was killed at a site in Libya where groups were fighting over access to Qaddafi-era munitions.
abstract: Investigation into the death of an Estonian explosive ordnance disposal technician finds that he was killed at a site in Libya where groups were fighting over access to Qaddafi-era munitions; technician, Kaido Keerdo, died in March while examining unexploded munitions scattered near a police compound and checkpoint in Ad Dafniyah as part of his work for the nongovernmental group Danish Church Aid.
lead_paragraph: An investigation into the death of an Estonian explosive ordnance disposal technician found that he was killed at a site in Libya where groups were fighting over access to Qaddafi-era munitions.

headline.seo: Death in Libya Shows Problems With Loose Weapons
headline.main: Death Illustrates Issues With Loose Weapons Stockpiles in Libya
headline.print_headline: Death Illustrates Problems of Weapons Stockpiles in Libya
